<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 96-12-22 - Rapid Acceleration Flutter Or Stumble, With Warmed Up Engine And No Load Condition</stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi961222rb" tsitype="engine">
        <tsinumber>96-12-22</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>September, 1996</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>ENGINE</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Rapid Acceleration Flutter Or Stumble, With Warmed Up Engine And No Load Condition</subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <engfamgroup/>

                <engfam>DT 466E
                    <snrange>931164 to 981119</snrange>
                </engfam>
                <engfam>530E
                    <snrange>931164 to 981119</snrange>
                </engfam>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <title>GENERAL INFORMATION</title>
                <para>This TSI incorporates information from Addendums No. 1, No. 2, and No.3</para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
        <svcproc svcproctype="TSI" graphiccount="0">
            <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
            <svcprocinfo>
                <para>Some of the above engine models have demonstrated a flutter or stumble-like condition during warm
                    engine acceleration under no-load conditions. The condition is most noticeable on units equipped
                    with manual transmissions. (Automatic transmission torque converter characteristics add load to the
                    engine which allows the engine to accelerate smoothly without flutter or stumble.)
                </para>
            </svcprocinfo>
            <svcsubproc>
                <title>Possible causes for the condition:</title>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Air entrainment in the fuel system created by a leak in the suction side of the fuel
                        system between the transfer pump and fuel tank.
                    </para>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Restricted fuel flow to transfer pump. Partially plugged debris screen, crimped or
                        restricted fuel lines from tank.
                    </para>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Low Cetane fuels. Fuels with low Cetane (below 45) have been shown to exhibit this
                        condition.
                    </para>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Poor engine speed and sync tooth detection by CMP sensor. CMP sensor application.
                    </para>
                </step1>
            </svcsubproc>
            <svcsubproc>
                <title>Recommended Action:</title>
                <para>If you encounter an acceleration flutter or stumble complaint on subject engines, follow these
                    recommended procedures to repair.
                </para>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Perform diagnostic procedures on fuel system in accordance with Diagnostic Manual,
                        EGES-145. Correct any leaks or restrictions found in the fuel supply system and test for flutter
                        or stumble.
                    </para>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Check fuel for Cetane number using commercially available test kit. If Cetane number
                        is found to be less than 40 operate engine on a known fuel which has Cetane of 45 or higher and
                        test for flutter or stumble. For this test, it is not necessary to replace fuel in tank(s) but
                        simply connect the inlet of the transfer pump to a known "good" fuel supply. If this corrects
                        the flutter condition advise customer of your findings and recommended use of higher Cetane
                        fuel.
                    </para>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">If, after performing the above two (2) steps the condition is not corrected, install
                        CMP sensor, (P/N 1 821 720 C98 (Black), with shims as necessary to/establish an air gap between
                        the sensor and trigger wheel of 0.025 to 0.035 inch. Use shim kit, P/N 1 826 583 C91.
                    </para>
                </step1>
            </svcsubproc>
            <svcsubproc>
                <title>Notes:</title>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">The black CMP sensor used with the DT 466E and International&#174; 530E
                            applications is extremely sensitive to air gap. Excessive air gap can result in high speed
                            misfiring condition. Insufficient air gap can result in poor cold startability. By carefully
                            following the attached procedure the proper air gap (for the sensor) can be successfully
                            achieved. Upon completion of this procedure, test for flutter/stumble condition.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">IMPORTANT</emph>
                            </para>
                            <para>
                                <emph type="bold">DO NOT CHANGE CMP SENSORS ON LATE MODEL ENGINES.</emph>
                            </para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">DT 466E and International&#174; 530E engines produced and installed in
                            vehicles after January 1, 1996 have had corrective action for the issue included in the
                            electronic strategy and calibration within the ECM. It is neither necessary nor desirable to
                            change CMP sensor type in these later engines.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">The correct CMP sensor for engines built after January 1,1996 is part number 1
                            807 339 C91 (Blue sensor).
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                </step1>
            </svcsubproc>
        </svcproc>
        <svcproc svcproctype="TSI" graphiccount="3">
            <title>SETTING AIR GAP FOR BLACK CMP SENSOR (P/N 1 821 720 C98) WHEN INSTALLED IN DT 466E AND INTERNATIONAL&#174;
                530E DIESEL ENGINES.
            </title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove existing CMP sensor from engine front cover and clean sensor mounting surface (
                    <emph type="bold">
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f9612221">Figure 1</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9612221" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9612221.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Manually rotate the engine at least two (2) complete revolutions, in a clockwise
                    direction when viewing the engine from the front. This is to insure the CMP sensor air gap is at its
                    maximum with the camshaft gear in contact with its rear thrust face.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>
                            <emph type="bold">IMPORTANT</emph>
                        </para>
                        <para>
                            <emph type="bold">BE SURE, WHEN MAKING THE FOLLOWING MEASUREMENT, TO MEASURE UP TO THE TOOTH
                                ON THE TRIGGER WHEEL. DO NOT MEASURE INTO THE WINDOW BETWEEN THE TEETH.
                            </emph>
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a depth micrometer or a precision caliper, carefully measure the distance to the
                    nearest one thousandth of an inch from the CMP sensor mounting surface to the camshaft gear trigger
                    wheel tooth (
                    <emph type="bold">
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f9612222">Figure 2</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ). Record this measurement in the appropriate box on the worksheet.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9612222" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9612222.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Manually rotate the crankshaft 180&#176; in a clockwise direction, when viewed from the
                    front of the engine and repeat step 3. Continue this process two (2) more times so that the distance
                    from the cover to the trigger wheel is measured at four locations. Variations in these measurements
                    determine run out of the trigger wheel. Variation should not exceed 0.005 inches.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a depth micrometer or precision caliper carefully measure the CMP sensor from the
                    tip to its mounting flange (
                    <emph type="bold">
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f9612223">Figure 3</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    )
                </para>
                <figure id="f9612223" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9612223.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Record this dimension in the appropriate box on the work sheet.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Perform the math as directed on the work sheet then select the appropriate combination
                    of shims from shim kit, P/N 1 826 583 C91.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Use the proper combination of shims to achieve a measurement as close to 0.030 inch as
                            possible.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the CMP sensors with the shims required. Insure that the shims are centered on
                    the CMP sensor flange. Use a small amount of grease to hold them if necessary. Reconnect sensor
                    wiring harness and test engine for the flutter/stumble condition during acceleration.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Use the following table to complete the CMP sensor air gap analysis, as described in steps
                            1 thru 7. Enter the measurements in the boxes on the table.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
